  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concern—it's a real, tangible barrier that I've seen play out in my own life and around me. Growing up in a small town near Kansas City, I learned early that being a person of color or a woman in a technical field could make it harder to focus on the work at hand. My father, who had a vocational diploma, worked with his hands, but my mother, with a bachelor's degree, often felt like she didn't belong in the world of engineering or mechanics. That tension between what you're taught and what you're expected to do still echoes today. Stereotype threat happens when someone's self-image is threatened by negative stereotypes about their group. In STEM, this means that if you're from a group that's historically underrepresented, you might feel like you're being judged or that your abilities aren't up to par. But addressing this isn't about changing people's minds—it's about creating environments where everyone feels safe to try and fail without judgment. I've seen this in my own work as a carpenter; when I'm working with younger people, I make sure to encourage them to think creatively and not to worry about being 'bad' at something. It's about building confidence, not just knowledge. The key is to start small—like having mentorship programs that connect students with people who've been through similar experiences, or simply making sure classrooms and labs are inclusive spaces. It's not about fixing the problem overnight, but about showing that everyone has the potential to contribute, regardless of their background. After all, in the end, it's not about who's right or wrong—it's about who's capable of building something meaningful together.",
